findingsText:
 This project has been successful in many respects. All stated objectives have been achieved. The major results include:
(i) An improved multi-scale embedding procedure has been developed that can treat nanostructured systems; 
(ii) The fundamental materials chemistry of transparent conductive oxides for photovoltaics has been extended to include knowledge of intrinsic limits to charge carrier control;
(iii) A new generalized code for assessing stability fields of photovoltaic materials has been written;
(iv) A quasi-harmonic lattice dynamic method has been exploited to treat the high temperature properties of metal oxides;
(v) The characterization of defects in low band gap III-V semiconductors has been developed;
(vi) UK-China collaboration on photovoltaic absorber materials (e.g. Cu2ZnSnS4) has been increased. (i) The multi-scale embedding procedure developed may be used by others to model different nanostructured systems;
(ii) The knowledge acquired on transparent conductive oxides provides a constraint on future device design;
(iii) The generalised code on assessing stability fields will be a useful tool for other modellers;
(iv) Details on the high-temperature properties of wide-gap metal oxides are of interest to understand their ionic transport properties;
(v) The defect characteristics of III-V materials that have been elucidated will be of use to experimentalists for testing fundamental research and in device design;
(vi) The fruitful collaboration with China can be of use to researchers looking to make ties with Chinese research institutes. Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Agriculture, Food and Drink,Chemicals,Construction,Creative Economy,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Education,Electronics,Energy,Environment,Healthcare,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology,Transport
